Bro my university's policy to get a new identification document when you lost yours requires you to publish a small advertisement in the newspaper asking if someone found it first, it's like a leftover legal rule from the 19th century that no one bothered to abolish, insane shit

When I was in highschool one of my buddies bought the worst car of all time for 300 bucks (~150 US dollars), genuinely every part of it was broken, steering wheel was fucked, roof was caving in, had to place a brick on the wheel when parked or it rolled, windows didn't open, etc.

Genuinely think it might have been one of the worst cars in the world, (at one point the same friend was also the person with the lowest ELO in our League server). I joked that he had to be careful with parking or some street sweeper could have mistakenly swept it into the trash.

One of my only regrets is probably not getting a really shitty old car to drive at that age. Seems like you can get used to driving anything if you go through a few cars like this, no power steering, no anti slipping ASR, just a bunch of metal and leather chained to an engine.

Thinking about how my grandpa (RIP, same one who got rammed by a cattle as a kid) had a brutal heart attack and spent multiple hours in excruciating agony while still refusing to go to the hospital, rubbed his chest with alcohol to try stopping the violent pain. Still survived it

It probably shaved like a decade off his lifespan and I miss him a lot, but also I just can't help but admire the stubbornness and insane pain resistance. One time he had a broken arm that was healing wrong and a doctor had to re-break the bone w/o painkillers, he made no sound.
Same grandpa also cut half his fingers on exactly a sawmill, left them right there on the yard and the cats ate them. Tbh I think some of us would act just as well in the same scenario
